            <div class="">
              <img width="800" height="800" src="https://peatlands.wetlands.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/2_800x800_2.jpg" class="object-cover fixed_image_ratio" alt="" loading="lazy" srcset="https://peatlands.wetlands.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/2_800x800_2.jpg 800w, https://peatlands.wetlands.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/2_800x800_2-300x300.jpg 300w, https://peatlands.wetlands.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/2_800x800_2-150x150.jpg 150w, https://peatlands.wetlands.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/2_800x800_2-768x768.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" />                          </div>
          </div>
          <div class="w-12/12 md:w-7/12 flex flex-col items-center justify-center py-8 ">
            <div class="two_card_content">
              <div class="two_card_title font-bold text-lg sm:text-xl md:text-2xl lg:text-3xl pb-2">Did you know?</div>
              <div class="two_card-content font-normal text-md sm:text-lg md:text-xl lg:text-2xl"><p>We supported communities in Indonesia to develop sustainable rural business models that marry protection of the peatlands, their carbon and biodiversity with strong livelihoods. Growing Sagu on peatlands instead of Palm-oil supports high water tables, prevents carbon release, reduces risk of fires and reduces subsidence that can lead to flooding. The sagu provides food and the wastes can be fed to ducks.</p>
<p>The Indonesian Peatland Partnership Fund has effectively supported local communities in the development of sustainable livelihoods.</p>
<p><a class="cta-button lightbox" href="https://peatlands.wetlands.org/indonesian-peatland-partnership-fund/">Read more</a></p>
